for assimilation. Nevertheless, the letters are an invaluable source of first-hand information on missionary work, residential schools, and the Haisla way of life in the early twentieth century. Editor Mary-Ellen Kelm bookends the collection with an introduction and conclusion that provide historical and historiographical context, exploring the concepts of race, gender, and cultural conflict as they played out on the north Pacific coast.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHaisla IndiansxEducationzBritish ColumbiazKitimat. 0aIndians of North AmericazBritish ColumbiazKitimat. 0aMissionszBritish ColumbiazKitimat. 0aWomen missionarieszBritish ColumbiazKitimatvCorrespondence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aKelm, Mary-Ellen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552383841?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552383841423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552383841/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles